<section class="mt-12">
  <h2 class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest">What is PWT?</h2>
  <div class="mt-4 border border-neutral-800 p-6">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-400">
      Git worktrees let you check out multiple branches simultaneously in separate directories.
      Instead of stashing or committing work-in-progress to switch branches, each branch lives
      in its own folder.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-neutral-400">
      PWT simplifies worktree management. Create, switch, and clean up worktrees with short
      commands instead of remembering long Git incantations.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-12">
  <h2 class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest">Commands</h2>
  <div class="mt-4 border border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-900">
    <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 text-xs leading-relaxed"><code><span class="text-amber-300">pwt new</span> <span class="text-neutral-500">&lt;branch&gt;</span>     <span class="text-neutral-500"># Create a new worktree</span>
<span class="text-amber-300">pwt open</span> <span class="text-neutral-500">&lt;branch&gt;</span>    <span class="text-neutral-500"># Switch to an existing worktree</span>
<span class="text-amber-300">pwt close</span>            <span class="text-neutral-500"># Close the current worktree</span>
<span class="text-amber-300">pwt ls</span>               <span class="text-neutral-500"># List all worktrees</span></code></pre>
  </div>
</section>
